headline: Billionaire Cari Tuna on why the organization she started will offer free advice to other donors
summary: For San Francisco-based billionaire Cari Tuna, the most important decision a philanthropist can make is deciding what cause to support.  Starting Tuesday, the organization she helped found will offer help to other major donors making those choices.  Tuna, 40, and her husband, Dustin Moskovitz, 41, first seriously started in philanthropy in 2010, when Tuna quit her job as a journalist and set out to give away most of their wealth, which Moskovitz initially made as a cofounder of Facebook.

headline: AI boom will continue despite bubble fears: Arm CMO
summary: Arm (ARM) Holdings, the semiconductor design company that lists Microsoft (MSFT), Nvidia (NVDA), Meta (META) and Apple (AAPL) among its many partners, expects surging revenue driven by AI - even as fears of a bubble keep growing. Chief Marketing Officer Ami Badani spoke with Ramzan Karmali about the firm's strategy to expand across data centers and mobile devices, while continuing to push for more energy-efficient chips. For more live coverage of the markets, watch the full episode of Market Sunrise and visit Yahoo Finance.
